  <section id="methodology" class="data-section methodology-section">
    <h2>Methodology</h2>

    <div class="methodology-block">
      <h3>About the ACS 5-Year Estimates</h3>
      <p>The primary demographic data on this site comes from the <strong>American Community Survey (ACS) 5-Year Estimates</strong>, published by the U.S. Census Bureau. A "5-year estimate" is not a snapshot of a single year — it represents a rolling average of survey data collected over five consecutive years. For example, the ACS 2019-2023 vintage reflects responses gathered between January 2019 and December 2023.</p>
      <p>This averaging provides more reliable estimates for small geographies (like Census block groups), but it means that the figures do not precisely represent any single point in time. In a rapidly growing city like Columbus, this temporal smoothing can mask recent changes — a district that added substantial housing in 2022-2023 will show a lower population figure than its current reality, because the 5-year average includes earlier, lower-population years.</p>

      <h4>Why block-group aggregation is necessary</h4>
      <p>Columbus's nine City Council districts do not align with any standard Census geography. The Census Bureau publishes data for tracts, block groups, and blocks — none of which correspond to council district boundaries. To produce district-level demographic figures, this site aggregates ACS data from the Census block-group level up to the district level.</p>
      <p>The aggregation works by mapping each Census block (the smallest Census geography) to its containing council district using the city's official block-to-district crosswalk (<code>CensusBlock2020_with_CouncilDistrict2023.xlsx</code>). Blocks are grouped into their parent block groups, and each block group's share within a council district is calculated based on population. District-level figures are then computed as population-weighted sums (for counts like total population) or population-weighted averages (for medians like household income).</p>

      <h4>Why median figures are approximations</h4>
      <p>When the site reports "median household income" for a district, this is a <strong>population-weighted average of block-group medians</strong> — not a true district-level median calculated from individual household data. The Census Bureau publishes median values only at the block-group level and above; there is no published median for a custom geography like a council district. The weighted-average approach is a standard and defensible approximation used by planning agencies and researchers, but it can diverge from a true median, particularly when income distributions are skewed or when block groups within a district have very different income profiles. The same caveat applies to median gross rent and median home value.</p>

      <h4>Margins of error</h4>
      <p>All ACS estimates carry margins of error (MOE). This site does not display MOEs on individual district pages to maintain readability, but users should be aware that every figure is a statistical estimate, not a precise count. At the population sizes of Columbus's districts (roughly 100,000 residents each), ACS 5-year estimates for major demographic categories are generally reliable, but smaller population subgroups (e.g., specific racial categories in smaller districts) will have larger relative margins of error. The Census Bureau publishes <a href="https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/acs/library/handbooks/general.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">guidance on interpreting ACS reliability</a>. To calculate a 90% confidence interval for any figure: point estimate ± margin of error.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="methodology-block">
      <h3>ACS vs. Esri Current-Year Estimates</h3>
      <p>Where available, this site displays <strong>Esri current-year estimates</strong> alongside ACS figures. Esri is a private geospatial analytics firm that produces forward-looking demographic projections for every Census geography in the United States. Their estimates start from the 2020 decennial Census as a baseline and update annually using building permits, U.S. Postal Service delivery counts, IRS tax-return migration data, and proprietary models.</p>
      <p>The two data sources serve different purposes and should not be treated as interchangeable:</p>
      <p><strong>ACS estimates</strong> are backward-looking 5-year survey averages. They are the standard for peer-reviewed research, historical comparison, and trend analysis. Use ACS figures when comparing Columbus districts to other cities, tracking change over time, or citing demographics in a formal context.</p>
      <p><strong>Esri estimates</strong> are forward-looking current-year projections. They are useful for current-year planning and for understanding where a district stands today versus the survey average. Use Esri figures when the ACS vintage is several years old and you need a more current approximation.</p>
      <p>It is normal and expected for ACS and Esri figures to diverge — the divergence reflects both the time lag between a 5-year average and a current-year projection, and methodological differences in how the two sources estimate demographic variables. High-growth districts (D2, D5, D6, D8, D9) tend to show the largest divergences because ACS's 5-year average has not yet fully captured recent population growth that Esri's models incorporate.</p>

      <h4>Income, rent, and home value differences</h4>
      <p>ACS figures for median household income, median gross rent, and median home value are systematically higher than Esri's estimates across all nine districts. This is a known methodological effect: ACS figures on this site are population-weighted averages of block-group medians, which tend to produce higher values than Esri's direct estimation approach. The divergence does not indicate an error in either source — it reflects how two different aggregation approaches interact with the underlying income and rent distributions.</p>

      <h4>Race and ethnicity classification differences</h4>
      <p>ACS uses Census Bureau definitions from Table B03002 (Hispanic Origin by Race), which classifies individuals into mutually exclusive categories based on self-identification. Esri applies its own current-year estimation models, which may handle multiracial individuals and small populations differently. In particular, Esri's American Indian counts include individuals who selected American Indian as one of their races (including multiracial individuals), while ACS B03002 counts only individuals who identify as Non-Hispanic American Indian alone. Both figures are valid for their respective classification approaches; the consistent divergence across all districts is a methodology difference, not a data error.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="methodology-block" id="known-anomalies">
      <h3>Known Anomalies Under Review</h3>
      <p>The following variances between ACS and Esri data are under investigation and are flagged here for transparency:</p>
      <p><strong>District 3, Asian population:</strong> ACS reports 9,739 Non-Hispanic Asian residents; Esri reports 24,075 — a -59.5% divergence. District 3 includes the Ohio State University campus, where group-quarters methodology and block-group boundary assignments may contribute to the discrepancy. This is the single largest percentage variance for a numerically significant population in the dataset and is under active review.</p>
      <p><strong>District 3, Black population:</strong> ACS reports 5,552 Non-Hispanic Black residents; Esri reports 8,354 — a -33.5% divergence. This may relate to the same block-group crosswalk issues affecting the D3 Asian population count.</p>
      <p><strong>District 2, total population:</strong> ACS reports 143,899; Esri reports 103,970 — a +38.4% divergence. This is the largest population divergence of any district. It may reflect genuine rapid growth in the Clintonville and Northland corridors, a block-group crosswalk issue, or both. Under investigation.</p>
      <p>All figures on individual district pages are displayed as reported by the source data. Where a figure is under review, the district page includes a note linking to this section.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* ================================================================ */}
  {/* SECTION: Data Sources & Vintage History (3D.5 continued)         */}
  {/* ================================================================ */}
